{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648376"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:53:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:53:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18308"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18308"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.16,0.08,0.72,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11026"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78525"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11026"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18308"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63866"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26901"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78525"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a complaint of numbness and tingling in the back of his right thigh, which has been present for the past two weeks. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He works as a delivery driver and spends long hours sitting. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals decreased sensation in the posterior aspect of the right thigh, with no motor deficits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves is most likely responsible for the sensory deficit?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inferior clunial nerves","Lateral femoral cutaneous nerve (L2,3)","Obturator nerve","Posterior femoral cutaneous nerve (S1-3)","Superficial fibular nerve"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior femoral cutaneous nerve (S1-3)\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for providing sensory innervation to the skin of the posterior thigh. It originates from the sacral plexus and travels down the posterior aspect of the thigh, making it the most likely nerve involved in this patient\u0027s sensory symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior clunial nerves\u003C/strong\u003E are branches of the posterior femoral cutaneous nerve that supply the skin over the lower part of the buttocks, not the posterior thigh.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral femoral cutaneous nerve (L2,3)\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the skin on the lateral aspect of the thigh and is not involved in the posterior thigh sensation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperficial fibular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensory innervation to the dorsum of the foot and the anterolateral aspect of the leg, not the posterior thigh.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eobturator nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the medial aspect of the thigh and is primarily involved in motor innervation to the adductor muscles, not the posterior thigh.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The posterior femoral cutaneous nerve (S1-3) provides sensory innervation to the posterior thigh and part of the perineum.","Understanding the distribution of cutaneous nerves is crucial for diagnosing sensory deficits and planning surgical procedures."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63866"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18308"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63866"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T09:25:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T09:26:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11026"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78525"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"up